04950nam a22005535i 9780773549630DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735496307 a10.1515/97807735496302doi  a(DE-B1597)654729  a(OCoLC)974528223  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 7aPOL0230002bisacsh04a336.71092231 aHeaman, E.A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTax, Order, and Good Government :bA New Political History of Canada, 1867-1917 /cE.A. Heaman. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b31 figures, 3 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCarleton Library Series ;v24000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tAcknowledgments -- tWealth, Poverty, and Taxes -- tConstructing Fiscal Federalism -- tConfederation, or How Not to Run a Tax Revolt -- tTax Revolt in Nova Scotia in the 1860s: Fairness and Region -- tTax Revolt in British Columbia in the 1870s: Fairness and Race -- tMacdonald to Laurier: Revolt against Liberalism -- tReconstructing Fiscal Federalism -- tTax Revolt in Montreal in the 1880s: Fairness and Poverty -- tCorporate Tax Revolt in Toronto in the 1890s: Fairness and Wealth -- tSingle-Tax Revolt in the 1900s: Fairness over the Land -- tLaurier to Borden: Failed Revolt against the Tariff -- tIncome Tax: Progressivism Triumphant -- tThe Politics of Fairness -- tGlossary -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWas Canada's Dominion experiment of 1867 an experiment in political domination? Looking to taxes provides the answer: they are a privileged measure of both political agency and political domination. To pay one's taxes was the sine qua non of entry into political life, but taxes are also the point of politics, which is always about the control of wealth. Modern states have everywhere been born of tax revolts, and Canada was no exception. Heaman shows that the competing claims of the propertied versus the people are hardwired constituents of Canadian political history. Tax debates in early Canada were philosophically charged, politically consequential dialogues about the relationship between wealth and poverty. Extensive archival research, from private papers, commissions, the press, and all levels of government, serves to identify a rising popular challenge to the patrician politics that were entrenched in the Constitutional Act of 1867 under the credo "Peace, Order, and good Government." Canadians wrote themselves a new constitution in 1867 because they needed a new tax deal, one that reflected the changing balance of regional, racial, and religious political accommodations. In the fifty years that followed, politics became social politics and a liberal state became a modern administrative one. But emerging conceptions of fiscal fairness met with intense resistance from conservative statesmen, culminating in 1917 in a progressive income tax and the bitterest election in Canadian history. Tax, Order, and Good Government tells the story of Confederation without exceptionalism or misplaced sentimentality and, in so doing, reads Canadian history as a lesson in how the state works. Tax, Order, and Good Government follows the money and returns taxation to where it belongs: at the heart of Canada's political, economic, and social history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFiscal policyxHistoryxCanada. 0aFiscal policyzCanadaxHistory. 0aTaxationxHistoryxCanada. 0aTaxationzCanadaxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z9783111273655